decor/99904">Source</a></figcaption></figure>
<figure data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_5053" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-5053" style="width: 2432px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img data-attachment-id="5053" data-permalink="https://medievalbooks.nl/2018/11/02/medieval-book-carousels/oxford_bodleian_e_mus-_65/" data-orig-file="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/oxford_bodleian_e_mus-_65.jpg" data-orig-size="2432,1624" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Oxford_Bodleian_E_Mus._65" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/oxford_bodleian_e_mus-_65.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/oxford_bodleian_e_mus-_65.jpg?w=474" loading="lazy" class=" size-full wp-image-5053 aligncenter" src="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/oxford_bodleian_e_mus-_65.jpg?w=474" alt="Oxford_Bodleian_E_Mus._65" srcset="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/oxford_bodleian_e_mus-_65.jpg 2432w, https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/oxford_bodleian_e_mus-_65.jpg?w=150&amp;h=100 150w, https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/oxford_bodleian_e_mus-_65.jpg?w=300&amp;h=200 300w, https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/oxford_bodleian_e_mus-_65.jpg?w=768&amp;h=513 768w, https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/oxford_bodleian_e_mus-_65.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=684 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 2432px) 100vw, 2432px"><figcaption id="caption-attachment-5053" class="wp-caption-text">Figure 6. One of the authors of Le Roman de la Rose, Guillaume de Lorris or Jean de Meun, shown with book wheel (Oxford, Bodleian Library, MS e Mus. 65, datable to <em>c</em>. 1390). <a href="https://digital.bodleian.ox.ac.uk/inquire/Discover/Search/#/?p=c+6,t+%22e%20mus.%2065%22,rsrs+0,rsps+10,fa+,so+ox%3Asort%5Easc,scids+,pid+fdc348b0-c5e4-4e97-843f-4395e4feb2cc,vi+40b50b2d-0d79-454d-bf3f-5d00abe79a9d">Source</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>Both individuals seen in Figures 5-6 are scribes. The first in particular is very engaged with books, which are shown all around him. Not only is his desk fitted with a two-tiered book carousel, there is also a book case present behind him (note the handy fold-away doors), as well as a wooden bench that doubles as book storage. This “book bench” is fitted with locks, so that its precious contents were hidden from thieves.</p>
<p>Even more sophisticated designs appeared just beyond the Middle Ages. Surviving from the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries are both depictions and actual specimens of book carousels that were not fitted with a horizontally turning platform, but that moved&nbsp;<em>vertically</em>. Carousels with this orientation can be fitted with a relatively high number of shelves, perhaps as many as eight or ten. In order for the books to not fall off, it was crucial that the shelves remained level as they were turning.&nbsp;The most famous of these is the book wheel shown in <em>The Diverse and Artifactitious Machines of Captain Agostino Ramelli</em>&nbsp;from 1588 (Figure 7). The engraving includes the complex mechanism that held the books level.</p>
<figure data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_5056" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-5056" style="width: 577px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img data-attachment-id="5056" data-permalink="https://medievalbooks.nl/2018/11/02/medieval-book-carousels/the-diverse-and-artifactitious-machines-of-captain-agostino-ramelli-1588/" data-orig-file="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/the-diverse-and-artifactitious-machines-of-captain-agostino-ramellie2809d-1588.jpg" data-orig-size="872,1280" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="The Diverse and Artifactitious Machines of Captain Agostino Ramelli”, 1588." data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/the-diverse-and-artifactitious-machines-of-captain-agostino-ramellie2809d-1588.jpg?w=204" data-large-file="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/the-diverse-and-artifactitious-machines-of-captain-agostino-ramellie2809d-1588.jpg?w=474" loading="lazy" class="  wp-image-5056 aligncenter" src="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/the-diverse-and-artifactitious-machines-of-captain-agostino-ramellie2809d-1588.jpg?w=577&amp;h=847" alt="The Diverse and Artifactitious Machines of Captain Agostino Ramelli”, 1588." width="577" height="847" srcset="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/the-diverse-and-artifactitious-machines-of-captain-agostino-ramellie2809d-1588.jpg?w=577&amp;h=847 577w, https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/the-diverse-and-artifactitious-machines-of-captain-agostino-ramellie2809d-1588.jpg?w=102&amp;h=150 102w, https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/the-diverse-and-artifactitious-machines-of-captain-agostino-ramellie2809d-1588.jpg?w=204&amp;h=300 204w, https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/the-diverse-and-artifactitious-machines-of-captain-agostino-ramellie2809d-1588.jpg?w=768&amp;h=1127 768w, https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/the-diverse-and-artifactitious-machines-of-captain-agostino-ramellie2809d-1588.jpg 872w" sizes="(max-width: 577px) 100vw, 577px"><figcaption id="caption-attachment-5056" class="wp-caption-text">Figure 7. A scholar behind a vertical book wheel, as shown in&nbsp;<em>Le diverse et artificiose machine del Capitano Agostino Ramelli</em>, 1588, fig. CLXXXVIII&nbsp;(Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University, Eliz+47). <a href="https://brbl-dl.library.yale.edu/vufind/Record/3433930">Source</a></figcaption></figure>
<figure data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_5059" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-5059" style="width: 573px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img data-attachment-id="5059" data-permalink="https://medievalbooks.nl/2018/11/02/medieval-book-carousels/leiden_bibliotheca_thysiana/" data-orig-file="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/leiden_bibliotheca_thysiana-e1541106892501.jpg" data-orig-size="2386,2719" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Leiden_Bibliotheca_Thysiana" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/leiden_bibliotheca_thysiana-e1541106892501.jpg?w=263" data-large-file="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/leiden_bibliotheca_thysiana-e1541106892501.jpg?w=474" loading="lazy" class="alignnone  wp-image-5059" src="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/leiden_bibliotheca_thysiana-e1541106892501.jpg?w=573&amp;h=653" alt="Leiden_Bibliotheca_Thysiana" width="573" height="653" srcset="https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/leiden_bibliotheca_thysiana-e1541106892501.jpg?w=573&amp;h=653 573w, https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/leiden_bibliotheca_thysiana-e1541106892501.jpg?w=1146&amp;h=1306 1146w, https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/leiden_bibliotheca_thysiana-e1541106892501.jpg?w=132&amp;h=150 132w, https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/leiden_bibliotheca_thysiana-e1541106892501.jpg?w=263&amp;h=300 263w, https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/leiden_bibliotheca_thysiana-e1541106892501.jpg?w=768&amp;h=875 768w, https://medievalbooks.files.wordpress.com/2018/11/leiden_bibliotheca_thysiana-e1541106892501.jpg?w=899&amp;h=1024 899w" sizes="(max-width: 573px) 100vw, 573px"><figcaption id="caption-attachment-5059" class="wp-caption-text">Figure 8. Book wheel in Bibliotheca Thysiana, Leiden (mid 17th century). Source: photo by the author</figcaption></figure>
<p>Early-modern readers also could opt to purchase (have built, presumably) a less elaborate carousel with a vertical orientation, one with a modest number of shelves, each of which fitting one or two books. The one in the Bibliotheca Thysiana in Leiden contains only four shelves (Figure 8). Its user, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johannes_Thysius">Johannes Thysius</a> (d. 1653), could consult up to eight books at the same time while sitting or standing behind the machine.&nbsp;The mechanism that held the books level is hidden inside the sides of the carousel. Even though you’d expect the books to remain on the shelves, it is quite a sensation to see the shelves remain dead level as you turn the carousel:</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<iframe title="VideoPress Video Player" aria-label="VideoPress Video Player" width="442.672" height="249.35321518987342" src="https://video.wordpress.com/embed/9yLXdojY?hd=0&amp;autoPlay=0&amp;permalink=1&amp;loop=0&amp;preloadContent=metadata&amp;muted=0&amp;playsinline=0&amp;controls=1&amp;cover=1" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="" allow="clipboard-write"></iframe><script src="https://v0.wordpress.com/js/next/videopress-iframe.js?m=1674852142"></script>
<p>Larger carousels than the ones shown here do not seem to have been around in the medieval or early-modern period. There were ways to expand the device’s capacity, however, for example by adding a stationary shelf at the foot of the carousel, or even placing the book wheel on top of a small book cupboard (<a href="http://initiale.irht.cnrs.fr/codex/10419">here</a> is an example). Cases like this show that book carousels may have doubled as book cases. After all, private individuals in the medieval period did not usually own a large library. The modest number of books they owned would normally fit on a book wheel with a horizontal orientation. In other words, in addition to being a handy device for studying or reading multiple books at the same time, book carousels were also most useful storage devices, keeping books safe and off the ground.</p>
